@database default
@node main "Contents"
=======
FaxGate
=======

Divert incoming email to a fax number.

@{"FaxGate" link FaxGate}
@{"FaxSpool" link FaxSpool}
@{"Install" link Install}
@endnode
@node FaxGate
=======
FaxGate
=======

Scans through your email directory, normally called 'uumail:' for any files
contained in the @{"'gateway'" link gateway} file, and bungs them into 'fax:spool/' for use
with @{"FaxSpool" link faxspool}
@endnode
@node Gateway
=======
Gateway
=======

Or  more properly, 'fax:gateway'.  This is a file which contains all your
fax numbers and email addresses.  Hence, if you want the email address
called 'strange' diverted to '12345' you would enter into the gateway file:

strange			12345
wierd			54321
bizarre			01811234567890

The fields are tab seperated, not space seperated, (sorry) so use an editor
that can handle tabs, like memacs.
@endnode
@node FaxSpool
========
FaxSpool
========

Ok, what this does, is scan your 'fax:spool' directory, and then convert
anything in it, into a group 3 fax document, and promptly bung it down the
phone line.  It then deletes the original file.

Why is this seperate ??  Because I process faxes ready to send after
downloading my email, and I fax them in the middle of the night.
@endnode
@node Install
=======
Install
=======

This is the hard part.  First of all, you should have 'elcheapofax'
installed on your system somewhere in your command path.

Then, copy faxspool and faxgate somewhere exciting on your system.  The ecf
directory would be good.

Add an assign 'Fax:' to your 's:user-startup' pointing to your elcheapofax
directory, somewhere to put the files.

Create a file 'Fax:gateway' with tab seperated fields for the addresses you
want to divert faxes from.

Make a directory 'fax:spool' so the program can put faxes somewhere.

Make sure you run 'faxgate' after connecting to the net.

Receive/send some email to your test addresses.

Wait till the phone rates go down, then run 'faxspool' and watch your modem
light up.
@endnode
